1
00:01:30,523 --> 00:01:32,548
[People chattering]

2
00:01:33,793 --> 00:01:35,124
[Knocking on door]

3
00:01:36,196 --> 00:01:37,629
You wanted to see me, sir?

4
00:01:38,932 --> 00:01:40,593
You read The Times this morning?

5
00:01:42,102 --> 00:01:45,333
Avershays Press
announced a deal with Irving Gattinger.

6
00:01:46,606 --> 00:01:48,699
Gattinger said that he was done with writing.

7
00:01:48,775 --> 00:01:52,575
Yes. He hasn't written a book in 10 years.

8
00:01:53,313 --> 00:01:54,905
It's a brilliant move.

9
00:01:54,981 --> 00:01:57,814
Based on name recognition alone,
it'll be an instant bestseller.

10
00:01:57,884 --> 00:01:59,010
BENTON: Yes.

11
00:02:00,253 --> 00:02:02,551
What do you think about Weldon Parish?

12
00:02:04,390 --> 00:02:06,790
Parish is one of my personal favorites.

13
00:02:09,129 --> 00:02:12,860
Why, are you thinking of signing him?
The man hasn't written anything in 20 years.

14
00:02:12,932 --> 00:02:14,866
All the more reason.
What do you know about him?

15
00:02:15,768 --> 00:02:18,100
Um, Weldon Parish.

16
00:02:18,171 --> 00:02:20,765
He left the United States in the mid-1980s...

17
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:24,435
moved to a small Italian village,
and, after his wife died...

18
00:02:24,511 --> 00:02:27,378
he simply gave up writing.
He's become a recluse.

19
00:02:27,447 --> 00:02:29,438
- He doesn't even give interviews.
- Hmm.

20
00:02:29,782 --> 00:02:32,410
We could sign Weldon Parish.

21
00:02:32,485 --> 00:02:35,215
We would set the publishing world on its ears.

22
00:02:37,257 --> 00:02:39,725
I want you to go to Italy and talk to him.

23
00:02:43,129 --> 00:02:46,064
Mr. Benton,
with all due respect, and believe me...

24
00:02:46,132 --> 00:02:48,760
no one would like to see
a Weldon Parish novel more than myself...

25
00:02:48,835 --> 00:02:50,530
it's just not going to happen.

26
00:02:51,371 --> 00:02:54,670
People have tried.
The man is just not interested in writing.

27
00:02:55,441 --> 00:02:58,274
Well, I expect you to make him interested.

28
00:02:59,379 --> 00:03:02,371
Have a nice trip. Goodbye, Jeremy.

29
00:03:37,784 --> 00:03:38,910
[Tires screech]

30
00:03:44,891 --> 00:03:47,155
[Bleating]

31
00:04:14,654 --> 00:04:17,418
[Women speaking Italian]

32
00:04:27,533 --> 00:04:28,591
Hi.

33
00:04:30,069 --> 00:04:34,699
[Speaking Italian]

34
00:04:35,074 --> 00:04:37,235
All the rooms have a private bathroom.

35
00:04:37,310 --> 00:04:38,800
Ah, you speak English?

36
00:04:39,846 --> 00:04:41,541
Does it sound like English?

37
00:04:43,049 --> 00:04:45,483
- Yes.
- There you go.

38
00:04:45,551 --> 00:04:48,418
Great. Look, I have some bags in the...
Excuse me?

39
00:04:48,655 --> 00:04:50,680
I have a couple more bags in the car.

40
00:04:55,028 --> 00:04:56,859
Perfect.

41
00:05:00,033 --> 00:05:01,091
Thank you.

42
00:05:01,167 --> 00:05:02,156
[Clearing throat]

43
00:05:03,703 --> 00:05:05,898
What, are you kidding? I carried the bags.

44
00:05:06,372 --> 00:05:07,669
I opened the door.

45
00:05:09,309 --> 00:05:11,174
You opened the door.

46
00:05:21,487 --> 00:05:23,387
[Headboard banging on wall]

47
00:05:24,090 --> 00:05:26,524
[Woman moaning]

48
00:05:36,636 --> 00:05:38,627
- Is the room okay?
- Yes.

49
00:05:38,771 --> 00:05:40,602
The room itself is fine, but...

50
00:05:40,673 --> 00:05:42,038
[Laughing]

51
00:05:42,375 --> 00:05:43,899
There's a...

52
00:05:45,411 --> 00:05:47,311
There's a couple next door to me...

53
00:05:47,380 --> 00:05:48,745
- and they're...
- Screwing.

54
00:05:50,717 --> 00:05:51,809
Yes.

55
00:05:52,218 --> 00:05:54,652
They come here every chance they get
for privacy.

56
00:05:55,822 --> 00:05:56,811
Ah.

57
00:05:57,156 --> 00:06:00,523
Anyway, I'm actually in town
looking for Weldon Parish.

58
00:06:00,593 --> 00:06:02,959
You wouldn't by any chance know him,
would you?

59
00:06:03,596 --> 00:06:04,654
No.

60
00:06:05,732 --> 00:06:07,563
Well, any idea where he lives?

61
00:06:08,935 --> 00:06:09,993
No.

62
00:06:11,270 --> 00:06:12,328
No?

63
00:06:13,005 --> 00:06:15,269
Really? He's lived here for 20 years...

64
00:06:15,341 --> 00:06:18,367
and you don't know him
and you have no idea where he lives.

65
00:06:19,679 --> 00:06:20,737
Yes.

66
00:06:23,149 --> 00:06:24,343
Right.

67
00:06:32,458 --> 00:06:35,655
[Men chattering]

68
00:06:35,995 --> 00:06:37,360
Weldon Parish?

69
00:06:38,531 --> 00:06:41,295
Excuse me, do you know
where I can find Weldon Parish?

70
00:06:42,735 --> 00:06:44,896
[Enquiring in Italian]

71
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:47,906
Weldon Parish?

72
00:06:56,449 --> 00:06:58,041
[Engine sputtering]

73
00:07:00,787 --> 00:07:01,947
[Speaking Italian]

74
00:07:02,755 --> 00:07:04,848
- Ciao, Bernardo.
- Gustavo, buon giorno.

75
00:07:04,924 --> 00:07:08,382
[Both speaking Italian]

76
00:07:10,563 --> 00:07:12,292
[Gustavo speaking Italian]

77
00:07:14,300 --> 00:07:16,029
[Saying farewells in Italian]

78
00:08:09,255 --> 00:08:10,415
Okay.

79
00:08:10,490 --> 00:08:11,752
[Clearing throat]

80
00:08:11,824 --> 00:08:14,054
Hello, Mr. Parish. My name is Jeremy Taylor.

81
00:08:14,327 --> 00:08:15,316
[Jeremy clears throat]

82
00:08:15,394 --> 00:08:16,588
JEREMY: Hello, Mr. Parish.

83
00:08:17,063 --> 00:08:19,224
Hi, Mr. Parish. My name is Jeremy Taylor.

84
00:08:19,432 --> 00:08:20,990
Pearce Learner Publishing.

85
00:08:21,334 --> 00:08:22,733
Hey, Weldon, I'm Jeremy.

86
00:08:22,802 --> 00:08:24,770
ISABELLA: [in Italian accent] He's not here.

87
00:08:24,837 --> 00:08:26,134
I just thought I would tell you...

88
00:08:26,205 --> 00:08:28,765
so you wouldn't waste the whole day
talking to the door.

89
00:08:28,841 --> 00:08:30,206
[Laughs]

90
00:08:30,510 --> 00:08:31,807
Are you a reporter?

91
00:08:32,411 --> 00:08:34,902
Me? No. Why?

92
00:08:35,214 --> 00:08:36,875
'Cause Papa hates reporters.

93
00:08:37,283 --> 00:08:39,808
He says they are
the lowest form of human life.

94
00:08:40,319 --> 00:08:43,379
My name is Jeremy Taylor.
I'm an editor with Pearce Learner Publishing.

95
00:08:43,456 --> 00:08:44,787
That's even worse.

96
00:08:45,258 --> 00:08:48,887
He says that editors
don't even qualify as human life.

97
00:08:50,763 --> 00:08:51,752
Oh.

98
00:08:52,765 --> 00:08:55,962
- Well, it can't hurt to talk to him, can it?
- No. It could hurt very much.

99
00:08:56,035 --> 00:08:59,732
The last editor who came here,
he chased down to the water with an ax.

100
00:09:01,340 --> 00:09:04,707
Okay, well, I'll take my chances,
if you don't mind.

101
00:09:05,545 --> 00:09:07,479
Okay, he's around the back.

102
00:09:07,880 --> 00:09:09,142
In the cellar.

103
00:09:10,917 --> 00:09:12,384
[Stammering] Excuse me.

104
00:09:12,785 --> 00:09:14,252
I didn't catch your name.

105
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:16,048
Isabella.

106
00:09:37,977 --> 00:09:39,604
[Bottles clinking]

107
00:09:41,347 --> 00:09:42,678
Mr. Parish?

108
00:09:45,585 --> 00:09:46,745
Mr. Parish.

109
00:09:47,053 --> 00:09:50,147
My name is Jeremy Taylor,
I'm with Pearce Learner Publishing.

110
00:09:50,823 --> 00:09:53,189
I have to say this is a great honor for me, sir.

111
00:09:53,693 --> 00:09:55,923
[Speaking imaginary language]

112
00:09:56,095 --> 00:09:57,187
What?

113
00:09:58,931 --> 00:10:01,126
Yes, I know he's here. He's talking to me.

114
00:10:02,234 --> 00:10:04,202
Can't you see he's talking to me?

115
00:10:06,639 --> 00:10:08,004
Who are you talking to?

116
00:10:08,107 --> 00:10:11,008
The king of the elfin realm.
The all-knowing little one.

117
00:10:11,410 --> 00:10:13,901
We're having Spam for lunch.
Do you like Spam?

118
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:16,407
[Smacking lips] I like mine with raisins.

119
00:10:17,550 --> 00:10:20,178
Um, you are Weldon Parish?

120
00:10:23,155 --> 00:10:24,247
The writer?

121
00:10:24,857 --> 00:10:25,846
[Laughing]

122
00:10:26,692 --> 00:10:27,989
They say I am.

123
00:10:30,196 --> 00:10:32,027
Were you looking for someone else?

124
00:10:35,668 --> 00:10:37,067
Yes, I think I was.

125
00:10:42,575 --> 00:10:43,803
[Weldon giggling]

126
00:10:44,043 --> 00:10:45,601
[Weldon smacking lips]

127
00:10:50,116 --> 00:10:51,447
Okay, okay.

128
00:10:52,551 --> 00:10:53,848
Hold on a second.

129
00:10:54,787 --> 00:10:56,049
Did you find him?

130
00:10:57,289 --> 00:10:58,483
Yes, I found him.

131
00:10:59,959 --> 00:11:01,256
What happened to him?

132
00:11:02,995 --> 00:11:04,292
No one really knows.

133
00:11:04,797 --> 00:11:06,128
His mind just broke.

134
00:11:07,767 --> 00:11:09,530
That's why everybody protects him?

135
00:11:10,403 --> 00:11:11,563
Is.

136
00:11:13,239 --> 00:11:14,900
It's just such a waste.

137
00:11:17,410 --> 00:11:19,776
I'm gonna check out
in the morning, if that's okay.

138
00:11:19,845 --> 00:11:20,937
Bene.

139
00:11:23,416 --> 00:11:24,747
[People chattering]

140
00:11:29,588 --> 00:11:31,055
GUSTAVO: He just came in.

141
00:11:31,123 --> 00:11:33,853
No, he thinks you're completely crazy, Weldon.

142
00:11:33,926 --> 00:11:36,326
He's leaving tomorrow, okay? Ciao, ciao.

143
00:11:42,268 --> 00:11:45,431
[Oboe music playing]

144
00:11:47,940 --> 00:11:49,908
[Birds chirping]

145
00:11:50,476 --> 00:11:53,912
That was a pretty elaborate ploy
to get me to go away, don't you think?

146
00:11:55,147 --> 00:11:57,342
Apparently it wasn't elaborate enough.

147
00:12:01,220 --> 00:12:04,917
- Mr. Parish, I came a long way to see you.
- I didn't ask you to.

148
00:12:05,725 --> 00:12:06,885
See ya.

149
00:12:18,270 --> 00:12:20,500
Do you know what "go away" means?

150
00:12:22,041 --> 00:12:24,601
All I'm asking for is a few minutes of your time.

151
00:12:26,045 --> 00:12:27,239
[Squishing]

152
00:12:30,316 --> 00:12:32,307
You're not going to go away, are you?

153
00:12:33,719 --> 00:12:36,210
Uh, I'm sorry to be so persistent...

154
00:12:36,288 --> 00:12:39,348
but nobody ever got anywhere
by taking no for an answer, right?

155
00:12:40,493 --> 00:12:42,859
All right, make your pitch.

156
00:12:45,631 --> 00:12:48,122
As I said before,
I'm with Pearce Learner Publishing...

157
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:52,034
a place where we pride ourselves
on being able to work with creative individuals.

158
00:12:52,104 --> 00:12:54,538
We believe in bringing
the writer's vision to the page.

159
00:12:54,607 --> 00:12:57,167
And as a writer myself,
I understand how important that is.

160
00:12:57,243 --> 00:12:58,369
What do you write?

161
00:12:59,245 --> 00:13:02,305
Well, I'm actually still working
on my first novel.

162
00:13:02,515 --> 00:13:07,009
And, I don't even know if it's any good,
but I have always dreamed of being a writer.

163
00:13:07,086 --> 00:13:09,577
And being a writer,
you think you can understand me?

164
00:13:11,657 --> 00:13:13,557
- Well, yes.
- Well, you can't.

165
00:13:14,794 --> 00:13:16,523
Actually, Mr. Parish,
I think if you were to give me...

166
00:13:16,595 --> 00:13:19,189
Look, you made your pitch, I'm not interested.

167
00:13:19,265 --> 00:13:21,233
- But I'm not finished.
- Yes, you are.

168
00:13:22,101 --> 00:13:23,500
[Whistling]

169
00:13:27,106 --> 00:13:28,232
That's Bruno.

170
00:13:28,340 --> 00:13:30,501
Bruno dislikes strangers more than I do.

171
00:13:30,576 --> 00:13:31,634
[Barking]

172
00:13:31,710 --> 00:13:34,941
- Now would be a good time to start running.
- What?

173
00:13:36,282 --> 00:13:38,250
Oh, my God. Oh, my God!

174
00:13:39,051 --> 00:13:40,040
[Laughing]

175
00:13:41,387 --> 00:13:42,411
[Thudding]

176
00:13:43,088 --> 00:13:45,249
[Groaning]

177
00:13:57,736 --> 00:13:59,465
[Cell phone ringing]

178
00:14:02,241 --> 00:14:03,469
Fuck.

179
00:14:06,545 --> 00:14:07,910
- Hello.
- Ah, Jeremy.

180
00:14:07,980 --> 00:14:09,140
How's it going over there?

181
00:14:09,215 --> 00:14:10,375
Hello, sir.

182
00:14:10,449 --> 00:14:12,110
[Clicking tongue] Not well.

183
00:14:12,184 --> 00:14:13,947
Well, did you meet him?

184
00:14:14,086 --> 00:14:17,214
- Oh, yes. Yes, I met him.
- What's he like?

185
00:14:17,289 --> 00:14:18,278
Hmm.

186
00:14:19,058 --> 00:14:21,219
The word "unstable" comes to mind.

187
00:14:21,493 --> 00:14:24,121
Well, show me an artist that isn’t, eh?

188
00:14:25,231 --> 00:14:27,665
Well, I think I can say
with a great deal of confidence...

189
00:14:27,733 --> 00:14:29,894
that the man is not interested in writing.

190
00:14:30,502 --> 00:14:33,232
Well, it is up to you to convince him.

191
00:14:35,140 --> 00:14:37,267
I'm expecting results, Jeremy.

192
00:14:38,110 --> 00:14:39,304
Jeremy?

193
00:14:39,478 --> 00:14:40,604
Jeremy, are you there?

194
00:14:40,679 --> 00:14:43,614
Yes, yes. Sorry, I'm still here,
but you know what? I've actually...

195
00:14:43,682 --> 00:14:45,149
I've gotta run right now.
Can I call you back later?

196
00:14:45,217 --> 00:14:46,343
Perfect. Thank you. Bye.

197
00:14:52,925 --> 00:14:55,416
[Women chattering in Italian]

198
00:14:55,494 --> 00:14:56,722
[Footsteps clattering]

199
00:15:01,567 --> 00:15:03,091
WOMEN: Ciao.

200
00:15:04,336 --> 00:15:06,133
- Hi.
- Hi.

201
00:15:06,305 --> 00:15:08,569
I heard about what happened this afternoon.

202
00:15:09,475 --> 00:15:11,033
The dog. Yeah.

203
00:15:11,710 --> 00:15:13,644
Yeah, your father's a very funny man.

204
00:15:13,913 --> 00:15:16,541
I'm so sorry. I tried to warn you.

205
00:15:19,518 --> 00:15:21,748
So, where are you going?

206
00:15:23,756 --> 00:15:28,659
- I was actually just looking for a place to eat.
- Oh. Okay, well, there's only one place.

207
00:15:30,963 --> 00:15:32,692
You would like that I take you?

208
00:15:34,833 --> 00:15:37,563
- Yes. Yes, I would.
- Come.

209
00:15:39,372 --> 00:15:40,566
Have you decided?

210
00:15:41,874 --> 00:15:45,469
- No. We haven't seen the menus yet.
- There is no menu, only specials.

211
00:15:45,778 --> 00:15:47,609
[People chattering]

212
00:15:47,680 --> 00:15:49,341
Okay, then what are the specials?

213
00:15:49,515 --> 00:15:52,040
Mixed green salad and spaghetti with pesto.

214
00:15:53,853 --> 00:15:56,185
- Anything else?
- No.

215
00:15:58,557 --> 00:16:01,720
Perfect. Then can I have a mixed green salad
and some spaghetti with pesto?

216
00:16:01,794 --> 00:16:04,922
- Excellent choice. Isabella?
- I've eaten.

217
00:16:06,665 --> 00:16:07,757
All right.

218
00:16:09,101 --> 00:16:11,968
You know, if you've eaten,
you really don't have to stay here with me.

219
00:16:12,038 --> 00:16:14,438
No. People shouldn't eat alone.

220
00:16:15,808 --> 00:16:18,106
I eat alone all the time, so I'm used to it.

221
00:16:19,612 --> 00:16:22,240
You changed your hair. It looks good.

222
00:16:23,816 --> 00:16:24,874
Really?

223
00:16:27,453 --> 00:16:28,511
Thank you.

224
00:16:32,158 --> 00:16:33,921
So, Isabella...

225
00:16:35,428 --> 00:16:37,191
what is it that you do here?

226
00:16:38,531 --> 00:16:42,194
I work with my horses, I help with the vineyard.

227
00:16:43,669 --> 00:16:45,603
That doesn't sound too bad to me.

228
00:16:47,206 --> 00:16:49,265
Your father seems to have adapted well.

229
00:16:50,276 --> 00:16:52,506
Well, my father is not an ordinary man.

230
00:16:53,012 --> 00:16:54,912
Why do you want him to write so bad?

231
00:16:56,615 --> 00:16:57,809
Well...

232
00:16:58,851 --> 00:17:00,284
- Honestly?
- Mmm-hmm.

233
00:17:04,423 --> 00:17:07,392
When I was 12 years old,
I broke my collarbone...

234
00:17:07,726 --> 00:17:09,557
so I had to stay in bed for five weeks.

235
00:17:09,628 --> 00:17:10,993
And I don't know if you've ever tried...

236
00:17:11,063 --> 00:17:14,157
but it's not easy
to keep a 12-year-old in bed for five weeks.

237
00:17:14,333 --> 00:17:16,198
One day, my aunt brings me a book...

238
00:17:16,702 --> 00:17:18,761
The Shadow Dancer by Weldon Parish...

239
00:17:19,839 --> 00:17:22,706
and, as I'm reading this book...

240
00:17:22,875 --> 00:17:25,469
something absolutely miraculous
happens to me.

241
00:17:25,744 --> 00:17:27,974
I am transported into a different world...

242
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:30,641
and every day for five weeks,
I lived through those words.

243
00:17:30,716 --> 00:17:31,774
And to have the talent...

244
00:17:31,851 --> 00:17:34,115
to instill those kinds of feelings
in other people is a gift...

245
00:17:34,186 --> 00:17:37,622
and it just should not be wasted.

246
00:17:38,524 --> 00:17:41,960
- You should have spoken to him like that.
- Like what?

247
00:17:42,027 --> 00:17:46,225
I see the passion that you have for his work.
You should have let him see it.

248
00:17:46,632 --> 00:17:48,600
- Well, I tried.
- No.

249
00:17:48,834 --> 00:17:51,530
You tried to sell him, and I know my father.

250
00:17:52,037 --> 00:17:55,598
He responds to honesty.
You should have tried using some.

251
00:17:58,844 --> 00:18:00,812
If you want another chance...

252
00:18:03,916 --> 00:18:05,383
he'll be at Carina's later.

253
00:18:05,451 --> 00:18:07,510
It's a bar just outside of town.

254
00:18:10,656 --> 00:18:13,682
[Mandolin music playing]

255
00:18:14,460 --> 00:18:16,325
[People chattering]

256
00:18:17,396 --> 00:18:18,920
You don't have the straight.

257
00:18:20,166 --> 00:18:23,260
That, my dear friend,
you will have to pay to find out.

258
00:18:24,436 --> 00:18:25,926
This is interesting.

259
00:18:26,338 --> 00:18:30,274
You're acting like you have it.
You're trying to make me believe you have it.

260
00:18:30,442 --> 00:18:33,468
- So?
- So, in a way, you're lying.

261
00:18:34,246 --> 00:18:35,907
Priests shouldn't lie, Giovanni.

262
00:18:36,148 --> 00:18:39,379
There is no lying in poker.
There is only bluffing.

263
00:18:39,552 --> 00:18:41,383
And God forgives bluffing.

264
00:18:50,596 --> 00:18:53,258
[People chattering]

265
00:18:55,935 --> 00:18:57,562
[Chattering stops]

266
00:19:02,575 --> 00:19:05,009
[Chattering resumes]

267
00:19:12,318 --> 00:19:14,582
What, I can't come have a drink at the bar?

268
00:19:14,653 --> 00:19:16,712
You could have a drink at the hotel.

269
00:19:17,790 --> 00:19:21,954
- Well, I would have, but there's no one there.
- Well, boo-hoo.

270
00:19:25,431 --> 00:19:27,126
Why don't you let me buy you a drink?

271
00:19:27,199 --> 00:19:29,861
Just so you know,
there's no hard feelings about today.

272
00:19:36,742 --> 00:19:37,902
Thank you.

273
00:19:45,784 --> 00:19:49,720
[All toasting in Italian]

274
00:19:55,394 --> 00:19:58,625
Okay. Why don't you ask it? Then you can go.

275
00:20:00,132 --> 00:20:01,156
Ask what?

276
00:20:01,233 --> 00:20:03,258
The question
that's burning a hole in your little brain.

277
00:20:03,335 --> 00:20:04,768
Why did I stop writing?

278
00:20:05,838 --> 00:20:08,602
Okay. Why did you stop writing?

279
00:20:08,974 --> 00:20:11,169
I didn't have anything else to say, Ollie.

280
00:20:12,278 --> 00:20:14,007
Okay, it's that's simple.

281
00:20:14,580 --> 00:20:15,672
WELDON: Now you can go.

282
00:20:15,748 --> 00:20:17,375
A writer always has something to say.

283
00:20:17,449 --> 00:20:21,749
Oh, now you're an authority.
How the hell do you know what I have to say?

284
00:20:21,820 --> 00:20:25,312
- No, no, no. Mr. Parish, all I'm...
- Look, we said we'd have a drink.

285
00:20:25,391 --> 00:20:27,791
I don't remember anything
about a conversation.

286
00:20:28,227 --> 00:20:31,719
The mere act of accepting an invitation
to have a drink...

287
00:20:31,797 --> 00:20:33,856
implies a certain degree of conversation.

288
00:20:33,932 --> 00:20:37,424
- I hope you don't write like you talk.
- Why? How do I talk?

289
00:20:37,503 --> 00:20:39,027
WELDON: Like an uptight jockstrap.

290
00:20:40,939 --> 00:20:43,203
Okay. What would you have said?

291
00:20:43,275 --> 00:20:45,300
Actually, I wouldn't have said anything.

292
00:20:45,377 --> 00:20:48,175
I would have gotten the hint
about not wanting to talk.

293
00:20:52,284 --> 00:20:53,774
You're not one of those...

294
00:20:54,053 --> 00:20:57,250
namby-pamby guys
that nurses a drink all night, are you?

295
00:21:11,437 --> 00:21:12,734
Very impressive.

296
00:21:12,805 --> 00:21:13,965
[Belching]

297
00:21:14,373 --> 00:21:16,170
Okay, hasta la bye-bye.

298
00:21:16,742 --> 00:21:17,766
No.

299
00:21:17,843 --> 00:21:21,040
I bought this bottle of wine,
and I intend on finishing it.

300
00:21:21,280 --> 00:21:22,372
[Chuckling]

301
00:21:22,681 --> 00:21:23,670
Eh?

302
00:21:24,917 --> 00:21:26,179
[Sighs]

303
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:30,712
[Chanting drunkenly]

304
00:21:30,923 --> 00:21:32,356
See you guys tomorrow.

305
00:21:32,725 --> 00:21:35,694
What do you mean, "see you guys tomorrow"?

306
00:21:36,628 --> 00:21:38,619
You said you were going back to London.

307
00:21:38,964 --> 00:21:41,660
No. You said I was going back to London.

308
00:21:42,801 --> 00:21:43,859
[Laughing]

309
00:21:43,969 --> 00:21:44,958
[Grunting]

310
00:21:49,541 --> 00:21:50,701
WELDON: Hey, kid.

311
00:21:51,777 --> 00:21:56,111
You're too... You've had too much to drink.
We're gonna drive you back to the hotel.

312
00:21:56,181 --> 00:21:58,741
Come on. Come on, come on. Come on.

313
00:21:59,051 --> 00:22:00,382
[Crickets chirping]

314
00:22:15,300 --> 00:22:17,097
[Men chattering]

315
00:22:23,108 --> 00:22:25,804
[Men singing in Italian]

316
00:22:28,380 --> 00:22:30,644
What's this?
You guys gonna rough me up a little bit?

317
00:22:30,716 --> 00:22:32,411
[All laugh]

318
00:22:32,785 --> 00:22:35,481
Hey, serious...
What's that? What're you doing back there?

319
00:22:35,554 --> 00:22:38,148
It's obvious that you just won't go away.

320
00:22:38,390 --> 00:22:41,826
Hey, whoa, hey, Father,
you just gonna stand by and let this happen?

321
00:22:41,894 --> 00:22:45,421
- This is God's will, my son.
- I don't know why you can't understand.

322
00:22:45,497 --> 00:22:48,227
I think I've gone to great lengths
to make myself clear.

323
00:22:48,300 --> 00:22:52,794
- Come on. I was just trying to do my job.
- Well, now you're going to join the others.

324
00:22:53,272 --> 00:22:56,298
- What others? There are others in there?
- They wouldn't go away, either.

325
00:22:56,375 --> 00:22:58,002
Okay, but I will. I'll go, I promise.

326
00:22:58,076 --> 00:23:01,068
I don't believe you. I think you're just
saying that so that I'll let you go.

327
00:23:01,146 --> 00:23:04,411
No, no. No, no. I will absolutely go.
Tomorrow. As soon as I can.

328
00:23:04,483 --> 00:23:07,247
- I think he's telling the truth.
- Yes! Listen to him.

329
00:23:07,319 --> 00:23:09,651
- I don't believe him!
- No, whoa!

330
00:23:09,721 --> 00:23:11,484
No, there's no need for this!

331
00:23:11,557 --> 00:23:13,388
WELDON: Arrivederci.

332
00:23:13,459 --> 00:23:15,051
[Jeremy exclaiming]

333
00:23:15,127 --> 00:23:17,493
[Shrieking]

334
00:23:18,730 --> 00:23:21,358
[All laughing]

335
00:23:23,435 --> 00:23:25,995
What does "go away" mean, Mr. Taylor?

336
00:23:27,973 --> 00:23:29,406
It means go away.

337
00:23:30,342 --> 00:23:32,310
I'll expect you to do just that.

338
00:23:34,079 --> 00:23:35,103
[Speaking Italian]

339
00:23:49,695 --> 00:23:53,222
I baptizing you in the name of the Father...

340
00:23:53,298 --> 00:23:55,858
the Son and the Holy Ghost.

341
00:23:56,768 --> 00:23:57,757
[Sputtering]

342
00:23:58,937 --> 00:24:01,770
- What are you doing?
- Baptizing you.

343
00:24:02,808 --> 00:24:03,900
I'm Jewish.

344
00:24:04,610 --> 00:24:06,009
Not anymore.

345
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:12,681
[Headboard banging on wall]

346
00:24:12,751 --> 00:24:14,946
[Woman moaning]

347
00:24:25,197 --> 00:24:26,528
[Whimpering]

348
00:24:31,136 --> 00:24:32,626
[Birds chirping]

349
00:24:33,939 --> 00:24:36,203
[Gustavo singing]

350
00:24:40,112 --> 00:24:41,340
Hey, ciao.

351
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:46,473
[Groaning]

352
00:24:50,188 --> 00:24:51,280
[Sighing]

353
00:24:58,230 --> 00:24:59,458
Unbelievable.

354
00:25:00,332 --> 00:25:02,960
You've got balls, boy, I'll give you that.

355
00:25:03,168 --> 00:25:04,635
And you've got my car keys.

356
00:25:13,545 --> 00:25:14,739
Here you go.

357
00:25:15,881 --> 00:25:16,905
Is that all?

358
00:25:19,851 --> 00:25:20,909
Yup.

359
00:25:42,507 --> 00:25:44,600
[Men chattering in Italian]

360
00:25:45,510 --> 00:25:47,068
You know what? That's not it.

361
00:25:47,212 --> 00:25:49,407
Because whatever reasons you have
for not wanting to write...

362
00:25:49,481 --> 00:25:52,712
I accept them as being personal,
but that's still no excuse for you to be such...

363
00:25:52,784 --> 00:25:54,979
an unbelievable!

364
00:25:55,687 --> 00:25:57,177
I guess I'm not for everyone.

365
00:25:57,389 --> 00:26:00,722
You know, I'll admit,
I only came here because my boss sent me...

366
00:26:00,792 --> 00:26:04,319
but underneath, I came because
I have always wanted to meet you.

367
00:26:04,396 --> 00:26:07,024
I thought that maybe
if I could meet the great Weldon Parish...

368
00:26:07,099 --> 00:26:09,067
perhaps you could
teach me how to be a better writer...

369
00:26:09,134 --> 00:26:11,796
but I realize now
that the only things you have to teach me...

370
00:26:11,870 --> 00:26:13,633
are bitterness and mistrust.

371
00:26:15,173 --> 00:26:17,869
[In Scottish accent] How goes
the grape business, Weldon?

372
00:26:17,943 --> 00:26:20,275
What brings you to town, Ian?

373
00:26:20,946 --> 00:26:23,779
I just finished my new novel
and came in for a drink.

374
00:26:24,249 --> 00:26:26,444
You remember how it was
when you finished a book...

375
00:26:26,518 --> 00:26:28,713
way back when you still had something to say.

376
00:26:28,787 --> 00:26:29,981
[Ian chuckling]

377
00:26:30,055 --> 00:26:32,046
Oh, I'm sorry. Did I strike a nerve?

378
00:26:32,591 --> 00:26:37,119
Ah, it must be tough being all dried up inside
and having to live on past glories.

379
00:26:39,197 --> 00:26:41,529
At least he has past glories to live on.

380
00:26:42,467 --> 00:26:44,059
IAN: And who might you be?

381
00:26:44,736 --> 00:26:47,705
- Jeremy Taylor.
- Ian McBain.

382
00:26:48,840 --> 00:26:50,501
Ian McBain, the novelist?

383
00:26:51,610 --> 00:26:52,599
[Laughing]

384
00:26:52,911 --> 00:26:55,436
- I know your work.
- You're a fan?

385
00:26:55,781 --> 00:26:57,874
- No, I didn't say that.
- Jeremy.

386
00:26:57,949 --> 00:27:01,544
Actually, I would say that
your themes are all the same...

387
00:27:01,820 --> 00:27:04,448
that your narration
lacks depth and imagination.

388
00:27:04,523 --> 00:27:06,889
- Jeremy.
- Your prose struggles for wit.

389
00:27:07,459 --> 00:27:11,122
Overall, your style is sluggish at best...

390
00:27:11,329 --> 00:27:12,887
and contains absolutely nothing...

391
00:27:12,964 --> 00:27:15,728
that your average Joe with a typewriter
couldn't produce.

392
00:27:17,335 --> 00:27:18,859
[Thudding]

393
00:27:19,571 --> 00:27:21,004
[Jeremy groaning]

394
00:27:23,875 --> 00:27:27,504
- He punched me in the nose.
- You'll live. I'll drive.

395
00:27:35,120 --> 00:27:37,680
Your trusty steed shall carry us to battle well.

396
00:27:43,428 --> 00:27:44,759
[Laughing]

397
00:27:45,597 --> 00:27:47,121
JEREMY: No, no, no, no, no, no.

398
00:27:47,199 --> 00:27:48,188
[Cars thudding]

399
00:27:48,266 --> 00:27:51,133
Oh, my God. Weldon, no. Please, please, no.

400
00:27:51,203 --> 00:27:52,500
Weldon!

401
00:27:59,478 --> 00:28:00,672
[Exclaiming]

402
00:28:06,251 --> 00:28:08,151
[Weldon laughing uproariously]

403
00:28:08,754 --> 00:28:10,984
That was great, wasn't it?

404
00:28:12,124 --> 00:28:14,058
You are completely out of your mind.

405
00:28:14,126 --> 00:28:16,617
- You know that, right?
- Don't you feel it?

406
00:28:17,229 --> 00:28:18,491
Feel what?

407
00:28:19,297 --> 00:28:21,527
- Oh, my God.
- Life!

408
00:28:25,370 --> 00:28:27,998
Will you sit down, you maniac!

409
00:28:28,240 --> 00:28:29,798
[Chuckling]

410
00:28:31,977 --> 00:28:34,537
Okay, I'm serious, stop now. Brake, brake.

411
00:28:34,613 --> 00:28:35,944
[Both yelling]

412
00:28:51,895 --> 00:28:54,523
We're having some people
up at the house tomorrow.

413
00:28:54,965 --> 00:28:56,432
Why don't you come by?

414
00:28:57,601 --> 00:28:59,125
Thought you didn't like me.

415
00:28:59,636 --> 00:29:03,436
I don't, but I dislike you
less than I did yesterday.

416
00:29:17,154 --> 00:29:19,588
[Woman singing melancholy Italian song]

417
00:30:33,697 --> 00:30:35,062
Ciao, Isabella. Weldon?

418
00:30:35,532 --> 00:30:37,261
[Speaking in Italian]

419
00:30:40,170 --> 00:30:41,228
Hi.

420
00:30:43,941 --> 00:30:44,999
Still mad?

421
00:30:46,844 --> 00:30:48,937
Someone could have got killed yesterday.

422
00:30:50,347 --> 00:30:53,043
In all fairness,
it wasn't entirely your father's fault.

423
00:30:53,317 --> 00:30:56,286
Exactly.
He gets into enough trouble on his own.

424
00:30:56,353 --> 00:30:58,048
He doesn't need help from anyone.

425
00:30:58,722 --> 00:31:01,384
But, look, I'm sorry,
but Ian McBain was saying...

426
00:31:01,458 --> 00:31:03,426
that he was all dried up
and living on past glories.

427
00:31:03,494 --> 00:31:06,759
I couldn't just stand there
and let him say those things.

428
00:31:08,031 --> 00:31:09,760
I love my father very much...

429
00:31:10,834 --> 00:31:14,531
but tell me,
which part of that statement isn't true?

430
00:31:15,672 --> 00:31:19,108
That's an awfully cruel thing to say
about your own father, don't you think?

431
00:31:19,910 --> 00:31:21,036
Really?

432
00:31:21,278 --> 00:31:25,647
- Well, yes. I mean, it's none of my business
- No. I know what you see.

433
00:31:26,316 --> 00:31:28,409
You see the great Weldon Parish...

434
00:31:28,852 --> 00:31:29,978
a man's man...

435
00:31:30,053 --> 00:31:33,284
a man who lives life
on his own terms, and others be damned.

436
00:31:35,859 --> 00:31:37,986
But you don't have to pick up the pieces.

437
00:31:38,662 --> 00:31:43,190
You don't have to watch a man
who was once strong and gentle...

438
00:31:44,401 --> 00:31:46,130
slowly destroying himself.

439
00:31:49,606 --> 00:31:51,233
How long has it been like that?

440
00:31:52,342 --> 00:31:54,139
Since the day he stopped writing.

441
00:31:56,580 --> 00:31:58,605
Are you saying
you think he still wants to write?

442
00:31:58,682 --> 00:32:00,240
Of course he wants to write.

443
00:32:01,084 --> 00:32:03,985
- Then why doesn't he?
- Because he's afraid.

444
00:32:06,023 --> 00:32:07,854
He's afraid that what was once...

445
00:32:08,458 --> 00:32:10,892
great about him is gone.

446
00:32:13,096 --> 00:32:15,223
He's afraid that Ian McBain is right.

447
00:32:30,013 --> 00:32:32,675
Jeremy, these are
my two other daughters, Dinnie...

448
00:32:32,749 --> 00:32:34,580
- Hello.
...and Maura.

449
00:32:34,651 --> 00:32:35,709
Pleasure to meet you both.

450
00:32:35,786 --> 00:32:37,048
WELDON: Jeremy Taylor.

451
00:32:37,955 --> 00:32:39,115
Buon appetito.

452
00:32:39,189 --> 00:32:40,520
- Appetito.
- Appetito.

453
00:32:43,994 --> 00:32:46,554
I didn't see you at mass
this morning, Mr. Taylor.

454
00:32:46,830 --> 00:32:48,559
Oh, are you Catholic?

455
00:32:49,466 --> 00:32:53,027
- No, I'm not.
- Careful, he'll try to convert you.

456
00:32:53,704 --> 00:32:55,899
I know. He's already tried, actually.

457
00:32:56,306 --> 00:32:58,365
What does it matter what religion we are?

458
00:32:58,742 --> 00:33:00,300
In the end we all die.

459
00:33:00,911 --> 00:33:03,311
There's no stopping the fact that one day...

460
00:33:03,380 --> 00:33:06,247
we all will be rotten corpses...

461
00:33:06,316 --> 00:33:09,342
in a dark, damp grave.

462
00:33:14,324 --> 00:33:17,589
[Toasting in Italian]

463
00:33:17,728 --> 00:33:18,786
Cheers.

464
00:33:23,066 --> 00:33:25,159
DINNIE: So what is it you do, Mr. Taylor?

465
00:33:25,269 --> 00:33:27,999
Why don't you all stop picking at him
and let him eat?

466
00:33:28,639 --> 00:33:29,867
He's a book editor.

467
00:33:37,314 --> 00:33:38,941
Yes, he's a book editor.

468
00:33:39,950 --> 00:33:41,781
I'm sitting next to a book editor.

469
00:33:45,355 --> 00:33:48,017
Please, try to make him write, my son.

470
00:33:48,592 --> 00:33:50,890
God gave him a tremendous talent.

471
00:33:50,961 --> 00:33:52,019
[Chuckling]

472
00:33:59,636 --> 00:34:01,126
FATHER MORETTl: It's true.

473
00:34:04,007 --> 00:34:07,374
No, I'm a priest. I'm a priest. I can't tell you.

474
00:34:07,444 --> 00:34:09,605
- You can tell me, but nobody else.
- It's a secret.

475
00:34:10,013 --> 00:34:11,275
[Doors opening]

476
00:34:12,015 --> 00:34:14,415
- Buon giorno.
- Buon giorno.

477
00:34:15,485 --> 00:34:16,918
How much do I owe you?

478
00:34:17,220 --> 00:34:18,687
[Speaking Italian]

479
00:34:19,089 --> 00:34:21,057
[Speaking Italian]

480
00:34:21,291 --> 00:34:22,986
Jeremy, this is Amalia.

481
00:34:23,360 --> 00:34:25,521
JEREMY: Pleasure to meet you.
AMALIA: How do you do?

482
00:34:28,365 --> 00:34:29,491
IAN: Weldon...

483
00:34:30,867 --> 00:34:32,801
that's the bill for my car repairs.

484
00:34:34,271 --> 00:34:37,399
I noticed one of my cows
was missing this morning.

485
00:34:37,674 --> 00:34:39,471
You wouldn't know anything about it?

486
00:34:39,543 --> 00:34:42,774
I've got her for safekeeping, till this is settled.

487
00:34:44,181 --> 00:34:46,945
- You stole my cow.
- Call it collateral.

488
00:34:47,651 --> 00:34:48,709
Excuse me.

489
00:34:48,852 --> 00:34:51,013
- Hello, Amalia.
- Hello, Ian.

490
00:34:51,388 --> 00:34:55,654
You're looking very beautiful today.
Could I speak to you in private for a moment?

491
00:34:55,726 --> 00:34:56,954
- I'm busy.
- Oh.

492
00:34:57,027 --> 00:35:01,521
Well, I just came by to ask if you'd,
if you'd like to go to the town party with me.

493
00:35:01,698 --> 00:35:04,064
I can't. I'm going with Weldon.

494
00:35:05,902 --> 00:35:07,301
It's news to me.

495
00:35:08,171 --> 00:35:11,140
One of these days,
you're gonna push me too far, Weldon.

496
00:35:11,208 --> 00:35:14,041
Yeah? Well, let's hope
you're standing by a cliff when I do.

497
00:35:17,681 --> 00:35:19,239
[Chuckling]

498
00:35:25,288 --> 00:35:26,380
[Sighs]

499
00:35:32,028 --> 00:35:33,393
[Clinking on glass]

500
00:35:39,369 --> 00:35:40,495
[Whispering] What?

501
00:35:40,570 --> 00:35:41,901
[Whispering] Get dressed.

502
00:35:42,105 --> 00:35:44,471
- What?
- Get dressed!

503
00:35:45,375 --> 00:35:47,366
[Mimicking] Get dressed. Get dressed.

504
00:35:49,345 --> 00:35:51,074
Seriously, what are we doing?

505
00:35:52,115 --> 00:35:54,083
Why, taking an evening stroll.

506
00:36:10,633 --> 00:36:12,260
WELDON: There you are, sweetie.

507
00:36:13,002 --> 00:36:15,232
I've come to take you home from the bad man.

508
00:36:15,304 --> 00:36:16,293
Weldon...

509
00:36:16,372 --> 00:36:17,498
